posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
"WHORES GET WHAT WHORES DESERVE."
There aren't too many Noise albums out there that can effectively build atmosphere without diving too deep into Death Industrial or Dark Ambient territory, however Snuff's sophomore release is an exception to this observation, manifesting insane ambiance through dissonant chaos.

It's very clear to find the influence Sutcliffe Jügend had on this record, from the unflinching squeals of feedback to the mean-spirited true crime theme. Snuff has both of these, but it's far from ripping off anything Tomkins and co. have done prior.

Snuff serves as a pseudo-concept album based upon the murder of 35-year-old Olga Piscugina (colloquially referred to as "Kristiina" in both the music and liner notes), a Lithuanian prostitute.

The reason I say "pseudo-" is because there's very little to do with the actual murder other than the description given to us in the first cassette pressing's xerox insert. ("The face was covered in blood and swollen[...]" / "Blood was spattered on walls, ceiling and [sic] doors[...]")

Side note: It's also been purported that the original pressing of the cassette contained a condom full of semen and menstrual blood. I have yet to see any conclusive evidence of this, as there are no pictures of the first pressing sealed, let alone the contents within its black plastic bag.

Listening to this record can feel like a chore for anyone who can't listen to a track for more than ten minutes. The latter half of the record is quite lengthy, but never overstays its welcome. There are very few parts that feel redundant, nor is there too much going on. Kristiina (the second track) has the occasional sample of a woman wailing in fear, which tremendously helps bludgeon the listener with the innate terror and density the record exudes.

Pour faire crac-crac les Sims doivent avoir une relation romantique assez bonne. L'un des Sims doit être dans le lieu désiré pour faire crac-crac et demander à l'autre de le rejoindre s'il ne peut pas être dirigé par le joueur.

>>176989844
>But I don't know how they all are related.
All come from the same proto-slavic root, coлдъ, meaning malt (which is sweet) In the east, ColC (coлдъ) turned into ColoC (coлoд), in the west into ClaC (slad). Compare "зoлтo -> зoлoтo / zlato" or with r instead of l: "гopдъ -> гopoд / hrad", "cтopнa -> cтopoнa / strana". Old Church Slavonic brought the western forms to the east, but usualy they have either a different meaning (cтpaнa) or are seen as archaic/poetic (гpaд, злaтo). I thought that would be the case here as well, but apparently the Old Curch Slavonic form was the one that caught on.

>Combinations
The verbs are initially challenging since that single word (verb) contains the object, subject, the verb itself and time. They're represented by "syllables".

I believe you have most of the information needed. You just need to organise it and maybe have someone help you make sense of it. The syntax is simple, with only a few of the rules having an exemption.
Why don't you focus on mastering verbs (vitenzi). Start with the "syllables" that come before the verb, practise those syllables using English verbs as I showed you. Once you're confident, start practising using Kiswahili verbs.
The key with Kiswahili verbs is to remove the vowel at the end if the word to get the root (mzizi). Practise with Kiswahili as you did with English verbs. Do not worry about the vocabulary (nouns and verbs). Get the syntax first.
>Ongea (Speak)
Root of the verb -onge-
>Pika (cook)
-pik-
>Tembea (walk)
-tembe-

Basic rules
The following appear before the root of the verb:
Subject
Time
Object
>Subject +time + object + root = verb

Appears after the root
Mostly used to add information on how the action effects the object
>Nunua (buy)....Root -nunu-
She bought me...
A-li-ni-nunu-lia...

I would advise you to avoid ngeli for now. Master verbs.

>>177031204
>>177031405
It's a textbook example of a weakening process, whereby a sound becomes more sonorous due to its position. The /t/ in "better" is surrounded by two vowels, and they spread some of their qualities onto it. As a result, it acquires voicing and loses its pressure buildup phase that is associated with stops, thus becoming a sonorant just like the vowels. It's not hard to see why it's physiologically easier to let your vocal cords continue vibrating when pronouncing a "voiceless" stop between two vowels, rather than keeping them apart. Similar processes are found in many languages.
> What would your reaction be if somebody talked with you using the first type of the sound?
Flapping is universal in Standard North American English. The case where it doesn't occur is overly enunciated pronunciation, which obviously is not natural speech.

Sometimes I fear you have a romantacised version of what it's like here.
The next generation are skipping Kiswahili as their social language, they're using English. It is not that Kiswahili lacks the support. It is a mandatory subject even in secondary school.

Kiswahili will always be a social language with its greatest strength being how easy it is to pick up and how it adopts to you.
>Kizuri chajiuza, kibaya cha chajitemebeza

Kiswahili is my main language, I like it. Try andbbe open-minded and you'll see how easy it is to pick up. My grandmother cannot write but she picked it up.
Learn the social version. Once you get the basics, you can properly formalise it to Kiswahili Sanifu.

Both seem fine to me, although there shouldn't be that comma in between the "nothing" and "but".

I'm not sure since I never had to consciously learn this stuff, however I think you only use a comma before "but" if it's being used to connect two phrases that could exist apart from each other.

Compare:
>There's nothing but water
>There's nothing, but there is water
The first sentence cannot be split as the word "water" has difficulty existing on it's own, however "there is water" is a full sentence, so the "but" gets a comma before it.

一筋 also means you're not interested in anything but the thing.
To give an example, 彼は仕事一筋だ sounds like he's dedicated to his work or he spends his life on his work.
